\begin_layout Title
Contracting on Cash and Carbon: mechanisms to reward countries for reducing
 emissions and paying out universal cash transfers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Lennart Stern, Paris School of Economics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Part*

\emph on
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Throughout the article we take the example of tropical forest conservation,
 in section (ref) we discuss how the proposals and result can be adapted
 to Carbon Pricing Reward funds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
to do: try to find indirect implementations of optimal mechanism with menu
 of options
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Various types of international mechanisms to reduce tropical deforestation
 already exist and further types have been proposed.
 The principal in each of these mechanisms is either a donor country (e.g.
 Norway) or an international institution (e.g.
 the Forest Carbon Partnership).
 In this article we will study how such mechanisms can best contribute to
 global welfare (in the models global welfare will be a weighted sum of
 the reduction in deforestation and the aggregate welfare of the people
 in the jurisdictions with tropical forests).
 It is for our purposes not important whether the principal is a donor country
 or an international institution.
 We will simply refer to `the principal' throughout the article.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An important design choice is whether to contract with governments or with
 private actors such as companies or individuals.
 The models developed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "emph{https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2957896}"
target "https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2957896"

\end_inset

, suggest that it might be more effective to contract with governments.
 In this article we restrict our attention to mechanisms contracting with
 governments.
 These governments can be at any level (national, state, local, municipal
 (see Cortez et al.
 2010) etc.).
 In the terminology of the UN REDD+ system, such mechanisms are known as
 `jurisdictional approaches'.
 Amongst jurisdictional approaches the question arises as to whether the
 principal should best contract with central or local governments (see Harstad
 2017 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "emph{https://www.sv.uio.no/econ/personer/vit/bardh/dokumenter/cc.pdf}"
target "https://www.sv.uio.no/econ/personer/vit/bardh/dokumenter/cc.pdf"

\end_inset

).
 It seems plausible that to the extent that the arguments that we will give
 are relevant, they weigh in favor of contracting with local governments.
 However, we will leave for future work a formal analysis of this question
 and will throughout this article take the level of governments with which
 to contract as given.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another important design choice (Chirouleu-Assouline et al.
 2017 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "emph{https://halshs.archives-ouvertes.fr/halshs-01643656/document}"
target "https://halshs.archives-ouvertes.fr/halshs-01643656/document"

\end_inset

) is whether to contract on deforestation policies (as for example the Forest
 Carbon Partnership's Carbon Fund does) or on results (as Norway does with
 Guyana, the Brazilian state of Acre and Indonesia) or on both deforestation
 policies and deforestation results simultaneously (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "emph{https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3086299}"
target "https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3086299"

\end_inset

for an attempt to model the analogous problem that arises for an international
 institution that contracts by conditioning its reward payments jointly
 on renewable subsidies (the policies) and the renewable energy produced
 (the result)).
 Throughout this article we will assume that the principal contracts exclusively
 on results.
 The results can also be applied to the case where the principal contracts
 exclusively on policies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A further design choice is whether to tailor contracts to each agent (which
 we will call a `non-anonymous mechanism') or to propose a menu of contracts
 to the set of all jurisdictions with tropical forests, who can then chose
 their preferred option from the menu of contracts (which we will call an
 `anonymous mechanism').
 In this article we will apply the models that we will develop to both of
 these kinds of mechanism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To our knowledge, all existing international mechanisms to reduce tropical
 deforestation are non-anonymous.
 However, this is not to say that anonymous mechanisms might not be implemented
 in the future.
 Indeed, anonymous mechanisms already exist in at least one other realm
 of international cooperation: the World Bank's International Development
 Association allocates aid to developing countries based on a mathematical
 formula (
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "emph{https://siteresources.worldbank.org/IDA/Resources/Seminar%20PDFs/73449-1271341193277/PBAIDA16.pdf}"
target "https://siteresources.worldbank.org/IDA/Resources/Seminar%20PDFs/73449-1271341193277/PBAIDA16.pdf"

\end_inset

).
 One rationale for this is to solve the Samaritan's dilemma (
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "emph{https://edi.opml.co.uk/wpcms/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/EDI-PF-PAPER-10-Bourguignon-and-Gunning.pdf}"
target "https://edi.opml.co.uk/wpcms/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/EDI-PF-PAPER-10-Bourguignon-and-Gunning.pdf"

\end_inset

) by making it more credible that the principal implements the mechanism
 as announced.
 This credibility rationale seems also relevant to the mechanisms we will
 consider in this article.
 A further motivation for studying anonymous mechanisms in our context is
 given in (
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "emph{https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2967170}"
target "https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2967170"

\end_inset

), where a treaty is proposed that could build on the existing CORSIA agreement
 to create a mechanism for financing several international institutions,
 including one contracting anonymously on reductions in deforestation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Throughout this article we can interpret the results for both non-anonymous
 and anonymous mechanisms.
 Before introducing the question that this article will address, it is helpful
 to consider an existing non-anonymous mechanism, namely Norway's current
 contract with Guyana (Busch, Birdsall 2014).
 It is illustrated in the following graph:
\end_layout

