\begin_layout Standard
Thus Norway pays at a fixed rate per avoided deforestation (measured in
 avoided CO2 emissions) relative to a pre-established reference level, until
 some upper bound of payments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It has been suggested (Busch, Birdsall 2014 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "emph{https://www.cgdev.org/publication/assessing-performance-based-payments-forest-conservation-six-successes-four-worries-and}"
target "https://www.cgdev.org/publication/assessing-performance-based-payments-forest-conservation-six-successes-four-worries-and"

\end_inset

) that Norway could add a clause to the contract that would oblige the governmen
t of Guyana to pay out as a universal uniform cash transfer to its entire
 population at least a certain fraction of the money that it receives from
 Norway.
 Such a contract is illustrated in the graph below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename C:/Users/DELL/OneDrive/Documents/norway guyana proposed.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The question arises as to whether anything can be gained from this kind
 of contract as compared to two separate contracts, one rewarding Guyana
 as a function of its achieved reduction in deforestation and the other
 rewarding it as a function of the universal cash transfers that it pays
 out to its population.
 More precisely: Suppose we initially have a fixed budget with which we
 optimally contract on deforestation reduction and another fixed budget
 with which we optimally contract on universal cash transfers.
 Suppose now we pool the two budgets and simultaneously contract on both
 deforestation reduction and universal cash transfers.
 Would it be possible to achieve more on both dimensions (forest conservation
 and poverty reduction) by contracting simultaneously on the two variables?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before returning to this question, we note that cash transfers are widely
 considered to be an effective measure to alleviate poverty (
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "emph{https://www.givewell.org/international/technical/programs/cash-transfers}"
target "https://www.givewell.org/international/technical/programs/cash-transfers"

\end_inset

).
 Making the cash transfers universal has the advantage of eliminating targeting
 errors, which are large in many existing targeted transfer systems (For
 example, in India's targeted food subsidy system (called PDS) only 28%
 of transfers reach the 40% poorest people).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moreover, universality reduces the potential for the system to be used for
 political patronage.
 Advances in biometric identification technology and in mobile phone technology
 for transferring money have lowered the cost of introducing a system for
 universal cash transfers.
 (Moss et al.
 2015).
 Aid agencies such as the UK Department for International Development have
 provided financial assistance to targeted cash transfer programs in poor
 countries (
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "emph{https://icai.independent.gov.uk/html-report/effects-dfids-cash-transfer-programmes-poverty-vulnerability/}"
target "https://icai.independent.gov.uk/html-report/effects-dfids-cash-transfer-programmes-poverty-vulnerability/"

\end_inset

).
 These activities can be interpreted as an instance of the aid agency contractin
g with developing country governments on targeted cash transfers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now concerning our question about whether anything can be gained from contractin
g jointly on deforestation reduction and universal cash transfers, let us
 first consider what we shall call `first best rationales'.
 Suppose that Norway is uncertain about whether the government of Guyana
 is benevolent towards its population or not.
 Suppose that if the government is benevolent towards its population then
 it will value highly the universal cash transfers paid out to its population
 (i.e.
 receiving reward payments that it has to pay out to its population in the
 form of universal cash transfers is almost as valuable to the government
 as receiving money with no further strings attached).
 Moreover, suppose that any reduction in deforestation that it might achieve
 will always be done in a way that benefits its population (e.g.
 through payments for ecosystem services schemes, PES, see Seema Jayachandran
 2017).
 However, suppose that if the government is not benevolent towards its populatio
n then it will hardly value at all the universal cash transfers paid out
 to its population.
 Moreover, suppose that any reduction in deforestation that it might achieve
 will always be done in a way that adversely affects its population (e.g.
 by forcefully evicting local populations and completely blocking access
 to forests 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "emph{http://www.cifor.org/publications/pdf_files/infobrief/6630-infobrief.pdf}"
target "http://www.cifor.org/publications/pdf_files/infobrief/6630-infobrief.pdf"

\end_inset

).
 Then if the principal (i.e.
 Norway in our example) could observe the types of the agents (i.e.
 the governments), it might be optimal to only make the government reduce
 deforestation if it is benevolent towards its population or at least to
 make the non-benevolent government reduce its deforestation by less than
 the benevolent government.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, more realistically, the agents' types are their private information.
 However, even then the principal can move closer to the first best allocation
 by contracting jointly on deforestation reduction and universal cash transfers.
 Indeed, there exist contracts of the form illustrated in figure 3 through
 which the government of Guyana will only participate in case it is benevolent
 towards it population.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This first-best rationale is even more striking if we switch from the interpreta
tion of the mechanism as a non-anonymous one to an anonymous one, as illustrated
 in the following diagram:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename C:/Users/DELL/OneDrive/Documents/anonymous combined mechanism.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here again the contracts depicted allow the principal to induce the more
 benevolent governments to reduce their deforestation by more, which could,
 if the first-best rationale is valid, increase global welfare (relative
 to the situation where the principal contracts separately on the deforestation
 reduction and the universal cash transfers).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are views expressed in the literature that would imply that the first
 best rationale is an important consideration (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "emph{http://www.cifor.org/publications/pdf_files/infobrief/6630-infobrief.pdf}"
target "http://www.cifor.org/publications/pdf_files/infobrief/6630-infobrief.pdf"

\end_inset

).
 In fact, concerns about potential adverse effects on local populations
 from policies to reduce deforestation have led several influential NGOs
 to oppose the REDD-mechanisms entirely (
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "emph{http://wrm.org.uy/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/REDD-A-Collection-of-Conflict_Contradictions_Lies_expanded.pdf}"
target "http://wrm.org.uy/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/REDD-A-Collection-of-Conflict_Contradictions_Lies_expanded.pdf"

\end_inset

) However, others have argued that these concerns are mostly based on problems
 in past REDD projects that contracted with private entrepreneurs or companies
 and that future jurisdictional REDD contracts would avoid such problems
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "emph{http://blogs.edf.org/climatetalks/2017/11/29/shoddy-cifor-publication-on-indigenous-peoples-rights-abuses-gets-the-facts-wrong/}"
target "http://blogs.edf.org/climatetalks/2017/11/29/shoddy-cifor-publication-on-indigenous-peoples-rights-abuses-gets-the-facts-wrong/"

\end_inset


\series bold
,
\series default
 see also Busch, Seymour 2016).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have already argued above that if one beliefs that there are risks of
 adverse effects on local populations from policies to reduce deforestation
 then this would provide what we have called a first-best rationale for
 jointly contracting on deforestation reduction and universal cash transfers.
 Now let us explore the consequences of a different view.
 Specifically, let us make the limiting assumption that the impact of deforestat
ion reduction on the population's welfare is independent of the government's
 enthusiasm for universal cash transfers.
 In this case the first best rationale for jointly contracting on deforestation
 reduction and universal cash transfers disappears.
 The question arises as to whether there is still something to be gained
 from contracting with the governments on the two variables simultaneously,
 given that the governments' types are private information.
 In other words: Is there a `second-best rationale' for contracting jointly
 on deforestation reduction and universal cash transfers? To put it again
 more precisely: For fixed budgets, would it be possible to achieve more
 on both dimensions (forest conservation and population welfare) by contracting
 simultaneously on the two variables? We will find that under plausible
 conditions the answer is yes.
 Moreover, within the models that we will develop we will be able to give
 some properties that must hold at the optimal mechanism.
\end_layout

