\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop 1 Under-conditions-detailed"

\end_inset

Under conditions detailed in this article, the type-complementarity property
 must hold at the optimal mechanism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the model from Armstrong and Rochet (1999) the type-complementarity property
 holds.
 In fact this result is a direct corollary of their complete characterization
 of the optimal mechanism.
 The main contribution of the model that we will develop in section 1 is
 that it extends the model from Armstrong and Rochet by allowing us to take
 into account that the impact on population welfare of money spent by a
 government depends on the type of government.
 It is plausible that governments that value highly universal cash transfers
 reaching their population are typically more benevolent and will therefore
 spend marginal money in a way that is more beneficial to their population.
 Indeed, in the literature on foreign aid (see Deaton 2013) it has been
 argued that increasing the money at the free disposal of non-benevolent
 governments even has a negative effect on the expected population welfare
 by consolidating these regimes.
 We will see that taking this into account reinforces the second-best rationale
 for jointly contracting on deforestation reduction and universal cash transfers.
 Moreover, the type-complementarity property will still always hold at the
 optimal mechanism.
\end_layout

