\begin_layout Section

\emph on
An extension to the 2 by 2 types model from Armstrong and Rochet (1999)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will now study a fairly general model of a principal contracting with
 a set of agents on 2 variables.
 It extends the model of Armstrong and Rochet (1999) to allow us to take
 into account that different types of agents will generate different contributio
ns to welfare from the spending that they undertake using their available
 money.
 In our application this is potentially important: The international institution
 (the principal) should be less concerned about leaving rents to governments
 (the agents) that are benevolent towards their population and therefore
 will spend their available money relatively well than about leaving rents
 to governments that are less benevolent towards their population and therefore
 will spend their available money relatively less well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will later on assume that the international institution has an exogenous
 budget.
 However, to prepare the ground, we will first establish results assuming
 that the cost of funds for the international institution is exogenous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The type space is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ L,H\right\} \times\{L,H\}$
\end_inset

.
 The first component of the type describes the `deforestation type' and
 the second component the `universal cash transfer type'.
 In our application the superscript 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 refers to deforestation and the superscript 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 refers to cash transfers.
 If the type 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{ij}$
\end_inset

 reduces deforestation by 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{A}$
\end_inset

, pays out a universal cash transfer of 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{B}$
\end_inset

 to its population and receives the payment 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, then his payoff is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t-c_{i}^{A}\left(x^{A}\right)-x^{B}+g_{j}\ w^{B}(x^{B})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}^{A}\left(x^{A}\right)$
\end_inset

 can be interpreted as the 
\emph on
subjective
\emph default
 net cost that the government incurs from reducing its deforestation by
 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{A}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, it could be different from the monetary cost of reducing
 deforestation for the government.
 The monetary cost for the government arises from foregone revenues from
 forest concessions, from expenditure on law enforcement, etc..
 The subjective cost might also be affected by political considerations.
 In fact, the results that we will obtain can be generalized to a model
 with the general interpretation of 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}^{A}\left(x^{A}\right)$
\end_inset

 being the subjective cost that the government faces.
 However, for ease of exposition we shall from now on assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}^{A}\left(x^{A}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the pure monetary cost arising from reducing deforestation for the governmen
t.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will interpret 
\begin_inset Formula $w^{B}(x^{B})$
\end_inset

 as the welfare that accrues to the population as a result of the universal
 cash transfer of 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{B}$
\end_inset

.
 We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{H}>g_{L}$
\end_inset

.
 The parameter value 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{H}$
\end_inset

 can be interpreted as reflecting a relatively benevolent government that
 values relatively highly its population's welfare.
 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{L}$
\end_inset

 can be interpreted as corresponding to a government that either values
 its population's welfare relatively little or that values only the welfare
 of some subset of its population (or both).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 the change (relative to the situation without any mechanism) in the amount
 of money that the government has at its disposal after it has paid for
 the cash transfers and for the measures to reduce deforestation.
 Let us denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{A}$
\end_inset

 the amount by which the government would reduce deforestation in the absence
 of the mechanism and 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{B}$
\end_inset

 the universal cash transfer that the government would pay out to its population
 in the absence of the mechanism.
 We have the following identity:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m=t-x^{B}-c_{i}^{A}(x^{A})-(-X^{B}-c_{i}^{A}\left(X^{A}\right))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that the change in the population's welfare relative to the situation
 without any mechanism is given by
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w^{B}\left(x^{B}\right)-w^{B}\left(X^{B}\right)+b_{\text{ij}}m
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is plausible that 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{\text{iH}}>b_{\text{iL}}\forall i$
\end_inset

: A government that is more enthusiastic about universal cash transfers
 (
\begin_inset Formula $g_{H}>g_{L})$
\end_inset

 might be more concerned about its population's welfare and thus generates
 more welfare increases per dollar of additional spending.
 (More on this in assumption 3 below.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The principal's objective is a weighted sum of the reduction in deforestation
 achieved and the welfare of the population:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
objective=z\ x^{A}+w^{B}\left(x^{B}\right)+b_{\text{ij}}m
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is the relative weight assigned to reducing deforestation.
 Of course the principal's objective function is the expectation of what
 we refer to as 'objective', taken over all types.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Comparing our model with that of Armstrong and Rochet (1999) we note that
 whilst our model is `more general' in the sense that it introduces the
 term 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{\text{ij}}m$
\end_inset

 capturing the effect of the money at the disposal of the different agents
 (in our case governments) on welfare, our model is `less general' in the
 sense that the principal's objective and the agent's objective are related
 in that both involve 
\begin_inset Formula $w^{B}\left(x^{B}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The government's informational rent is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r=t-c_{i}\left(x^{A}\right)-x^{B}+g_{j}\ w^{B}\left(x^{B}\right)-\left(-c_{i}\left(X^{a}\right)-X^{B}+g_{j}\ w^{B}\left(X^{B}\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(-c_{i}\left(X^{a}\right)-X^{B}+g_{j}\ w^{B}\left(X^{B}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 is the utility that the government attains by not participating.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We obtain the identity 
\begin_inset Formula $m=r-g_{j}\ w\left(x^{B}\right)+g_{j}\ w^{B}\left(X^{B}\right)$
\end_inset

 that we can plug into the objective to get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
objective=z\ x^{A}+w^{B}\left(x^{B}\right)+b_{\text{ij}}\left(r-g_{j}\ w^{B}\left(x^{B}\right)+g_{j}\ w^{B}\left(X^{B}\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The outside option is exogenous, so we can drop the term 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{j}\ w^{B}\left(X^{b}\right)$
\end_inset

 and write:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
objective=z\ x^{A}+w^{B}\left(x^{B}\right)+b_{\text{ij}}\left(r-g_{j}\ w_{j}^{B}\left(x^{B}\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 the Lagrange multiplier corresponding to the principal's budget constraint.
 The payment that the agent receives from the principal can be decomposed
 into two terms.
 Firstly, there is the amount 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}^{A}\left(x^{A}\right)+x^{B}-g_{j}w^{B}\left(x^{B}\right)-\left(c_{i}^{A}\left(X^{a}\right)+X^{b}-g_{j}\ w^{B}\left(X^{b}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 that he requires to be no worse off than he would be by not participating.
 Secondly, there is the informational rent 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 that he obtains,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $objective\ with\ included\ budget\ cost=$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z\ x^{A}+w^{B}\left(x^{B}\right)+b_{\text{ij}}\left(r-g_{j}\ w^{B}\left(x^{B}\right)\right)-\lambda\left(r+c_{i}^{A}\left(x^{A}\right)+x^{B}-g_{j}w^{B}\left(x^{B}\right)-\left(c_{i}^{A}\left(X^{a}\right)+X^{b}-g_{j}\ w^{B}\left(X^{b}\right)\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Again, we can drop the term involving the exogenous outside option, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(-c_{i}^{A}\left(X^{a}\right)-X^{b}+g_{j}\ w^{B}\left(X^{b}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

, and thus rewrite this as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
objective\ with\ included\ budget\ cost=z\ x^{A}+w^{B}\left(x^{B}\right)+\left(b_{\text{ij}}-\lambda\right)\left(r-g_{j}\ w^{B}\left(x^{B}\right)\right)-\lambda\left(c_{i}^{A}\left(x^{A}\right)+x^{B}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In line with the notation in Armstrong and Rochet (1999) we shall denote
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{\text{ij}}$
\end_inset

 the probability of type 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{ij}$
\end_inset

.
 In the case of a principal contracting with a single government (Such as
 Norway contracting with Guyana) 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{\text{ij}}$
\end_inset

 can be interpreted as the subjective probability that the principal assigns
 to the agent being of type 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{ij}$
\end_inset

.
 In the case of an international institution defining an anonymous mechanism
 in which all the jursidictions participating in REDD+ can participate,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{\text{ij}}$
\end_inset

 can be interpreted as the mass of jurisdictions having type 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{ij}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now give a definition for which we will give a more general version in
 section 2:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Definition 0.1
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def2 Definition-0.1-(in"

\end_inset


\series default
 (in section 1 this definition is used, in section 2 the more general definition
 from (Armstrong, Rochet 1999) is used)
\series bold
: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta^{A}\left(x^{A}\right):=c_{L}^{A}\left(x^{A}\right)-c_{H}^{A}(x^{A})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta^{B}\left(x^{B}\right):=\left(g_{H}-g_{L}\right)\ w^{B}(x^{B})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Assumption 1.1:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta^{A}\left(x^{A}\right)=c_{L}^{A}\left(x^{A}\right)-c_{H}^{A}\left(x^{A}\right)$
\end_inset

 is nonnegative and strictly increasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{A}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Interpretation: This assumption means that the two types are unambiguously
 ordered in terms of costs of reducing deforestation and that the difference
 increases with the amount of deforestation reduction.
 In order to stick to the notation from Armstrong and Rochet (1999), we
 have here chosen to designate the agent with the low cost as the `high
 type'.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Assumption 1.2:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{H}>g_{L}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Interpretation: The high type gives more weight to the welfare increase
 generated through the universal cash transfers for the population.
 In general this can be interpreted as a measure of how enthusiastic the
 government is about universal cash transfers.
 We shall, more specifically, informally assume that the high type is more
 benevolent towards its population (and is for that reason more enthusiastic
 about paying out universal cash transfers).
 This informal assumption will motivate our formal assumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Assumption 2:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda>b_{\text{ij}}\forall i,j$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Interpretation: This simply means that the marginal value of money available
 for the optimal mechanism is higher than that generated by just handing
 out money to any type.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Assumption 3:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{\text{HL}}=b_{\text{LL}}\leq b_{\text{HH}}=b_{\text{LH}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Interpretation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

: It is plausible that the more benevolent governments use money in a way
 that is more beneficial to the population's welfare.
 As far as the `ease of reducing deforestation' dimension is concerned,
 it is not clear how this dimension would be correlated with the benefits
 of additional government spending for the population welfare.
 It is therefore natural to assume that these two questions are independent,
 as we do here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on assumption 3, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{L}:=b_{\text{HL}}=b_{\text{LL}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{H}:=b_{\text{HH}}=b_{\text{LH}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For now we will take the Lagrange multiplier 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 as exogenous so as to be able to most clearly state our results.
 In corollary 2 we will deduce a result for the case where there are exogenous
 budgets and thus endogenous (shadow) costs of funds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The principal's overall objective now writes as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
overall\ objective\ with\ included\ budget\ cost=E(\text{z\ }x_{\text{ij}}^{A}-\lambda\ c_{i}^{A}\left(x_{\text{ij}}^{A}\right)+w^{B}\left(x_{\text{ij}}^{B}\right)+\left(b_{j}-\lambda\right)\left(r-g_{j}\ w^{B}\left(x_{\text{ij}}^{B}\right)\right)-\lambda\ x_{\text{ij}}^{B})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To simplify the exposition, we shall assume that all the optimal mechanisms
 are unique.
 (It is straightforward to adapt the propositions to the case where this
 does not hold.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Definition 1:
\series default
 Suppose we have a type space 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and two direct mechanisms, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}_{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}_{B}$
\end_inset

, contracting on distinct outcomes.
 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}_{A}\oplus\mathcal{M}_{B}$
\end_inset

