\begin_layout Standard
There is a wide range of views on what effects an expansion of the REDD+
 mechanism would have on the welfare of people in the jurisdictions with
 tropical forests.
 Whilst many NGOs support an expansion of the REDD+ mechanism, opposition
 by other NOGs thinking that such an expansion would adversely affect the
 welfare of people in the jurisdictions with tropical forests has caused
 donor governments to not contribute the money that they had promised (Busch,
 Seymour, 2016).
 The NGOs all presumably pursue objectives that are some weighted sum of
 the reduction in deforestation and the welfare of people.
 They also presumably share the view that since donor countries are rich,
 increasing their contribution to at least some relatively unambiguous programs
 like funding universal cash transfers to people in poor countries will
 increase global welfare.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Acknowledging that these empirical disagreements, the question arises as
 to what kind of mechanisms could use additional donor money in a way that
 unambiguously (i.e.
 under the various empirical views that the different NGOs hold) improves
 outcomes in both the main outcome dimensions, namely the welfare of people
 in jurisdictions with tropical forests and the reduction in aggregate deforesta
tion.
 One kind of mechanism that could achieve this is that of contracting on
 reductions in deforestation but requiring the governments receiving the
 reward payments to pay out a certain fraction of the money received as
 universal cash transfers to their populations.
 At the very least, this is a way of achieving compromise.
 Moreover, in this article we have provided results suggesting that there
 are also efficiency gains to be achieved from such joint contracting on
 the two variables.
 In the introduction we have provided a first best rationale for this, assuming
 that the pessimistic NGOs are correct.
 Moreover, we have shown that there is also a second best rationale for
 joint contracting that applies under plausible assumptions for all the
 views that the different NGOs hold.
\end_layout

